Europe WSJ Japanese Online WSJ-PRO-WSJ.com WSJSunday PTC RESTAURANT BUSINESS SERVER PAY SERVER TIPS TIP POOL TIP SHARING TIPS RULE TRUMP PROPOSAL SB126955385469309739639045841172100227009661 Acosta, Alexander Donald Trump Murray, Patty SYND CODES_REVIEWED Politics and Policy </DescField><DescField fid="ipcns">OPOL </DescField></DescTPC></MetadataPT><ArchiveDoc xml:space="preserve"><Article markup="pp0" lang="en" index="field"><HandL fid="hlp"><Title fid="hl"><SectionName fid="se" index="field">Politics</SectionName><ColumnName fid="clm" index="field"></ColumnName><Headline fid="hd"><Para lang="en">Spending Bill Curbs Proposed Restaurant Tip-Sharing Rule; Scaled-back version would prevent companies and business owners from taking a share of tips paid to staff</Para></Headline></Title><LeadPara fid="lp"><Para>WASHINGTONâ€”A pending regulation allowing restaurants and other businesses to require workers who receive tips to share them with colleagues is set to be scaled back in <ELink type="webpage" ref="https://www.wsj.com/articles/congressional-leaders-race-to-finalize-spending-deal-1521641432">a spending bill</ELink> Congress is expected to vote on this week.</Para><Para>Companies and business owners would be barred from taking a share of tips paid to waiters and other staff members, under a provision included in a draft of the bill congressional leaders released Wednesday night.</Para></LeadPara></HandL><TailParas fid="td"><Para>In a Labor Department regulation change proposed in December, President Donald Trump's administration sought to allow employers the option of mandating that workers who receive tips share that money with non-tipped colleagues. It would undo an Obama-era prohibition on the practice. The restaurant industry advocated for the change.</Para><Para>The rule, which is pending, allowed sharing with other typically hourly employees, such as cooks and dishwashers, as well as with managers. Worker advocates said the rule opened the door for restaurant owners to skim tips.</Para><Para>Under the bill, sharing would be limited to non-supervisors. The bill's provision would also allow workers to sue to recover any stolen tips with added damages and provides the labor secretary the ability to impose civil penalties against employers who steal tips.</Para><Para>Sen. Patty Murray of Washington, the ranking Democrat on the labor committee, said she brokered the provision in a negotiation with Labor Secretary Alexander Acosta. The Labor Department declined to comment.</Para><Para>"I'm pleased that Secretary Acosta listened, reversed course, and worked with me on legislation to make sure that big businesses can't steal their workers' tips," Ms. Murray said in a statement.</Para><Para>An advocate for the restaurant industry said he is pleased the bill continues to allow for tip sharing and removes the 2011 rule that barred the practice.</Para><Para>"Our concern is the enforcement and penalty language for unintentional violations goes too far," said Angelo Amador, executive director of the Restaurant Law Center, an arm of the National Restaurant Association.</Para><Para>Restaurants and other businesses would only be able to require tip pooling when the tipped employee is paid an hourly rate of at least the full federal minimum wage, $7.25 an hour. Labor laws allow workers who receive tips to be paid less, if they receive enough tips to bring their average hourly rate above the minimum.</Para><Para>The pending rule could have the biggest impact in eight states that don't allow for tipped workers to be paid a lower minimum. In California, for example, all workers must be paid $11 an hour, regardless whether they receive tips or not. Depending on state laws, the proposed federal regulation could allow for mandatory tip pooling in those states.</Para><Para>That would allow restaurants to tap servers' tips to raise the pay of other employees, without cutting into owners' profits. That could be important because restaurants are struggling to attract workers in a tight labor market. The unemployment rate in February was 4.1%, matching a 17-year low.</Para><Para>The food-service industry has the highest rate of job openings among major sectors tracked by the Labor Department.</Para><Para>Write to Eric Morath at <ELink type="webpage" ref="mailto:eric.morath@wsj.com">eric.morath@wsj.com</ELink></Para><Para>Read More</Para><Para>* <ELink type="webpage" ref="https://www.wsj.com/articles/congressional-leaders-race-to-finalize-spending-deal-1521641432">Congressional Leaders Strike Spending Deal</ELink></Para><Para>* <ELink type="webpage" ref="https://www.wsj.com/articles/congress-reaches-deal-to-fix-tax-overhauls-grain-glitch-1521649599">Congress Reaches Deal to Fix Tax Overhaul's 'Grain Glitch'</ELink></Para><Para>* <ELink type="webpage" ref="https://www.wsj.com/articles/lawmakers-win-some-funding-for-new-york-new-jersey-tunnel-but-standoff-remains-1521662335">Lawmakers Win Some Funding for New York-New Jersey Tunnel</ELink></Para></TailParas><Byline fid="by" index="field">By Eric Morath </Byline><Credit fid="cr" index="field"></Credit><Contact fid="ct" index="field"></Contact><Notes fid="rf" index="field"></Notes><Art fid="art" index="field"></Art><Copyright fid="cy" index="field">Copyright 2018 Dow Jones &amp; Company, Inc. All Rights Reserved. </Copyright></Article></ArchiveDoc><AdocTOC adoctype="article"><Item size="0" ref="distdoc:archive/ArchiveDoc::Article" type="arttext"></Item><Item size="0" ref="distdoc:archive/InvertText" type="invtext"></Item><Item subtype="primary" size="0" ref="https://www.wsj.com/articles/spending-bill-curbs-proposed-restaurant-tip-sharing-rule-1521722639" type="webpage"></Item></AdocTOC></DistDoc>

